dged by the evolution dispute that figured in only a minor part of his work, Rupke stresses context, emphasizing the importance of places and practices in the production and reception of scientific knowledge. Dovetailing with the recent resurgence of interest in Owen’s life and work, Rupke’s book brings the forgotten naturalist back into the canon of the history of science and demonstrates how much biology existed with, and without, Darwin  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNaturalistszGreat BritainvBiography. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  abiology, biological, science, scientific, academic, scholarly, research, darwinian, darwin, evolution, theory, theoretical, 1800s, 1850s, british, empire, england, united kingdom, europe, western world, scientist, lesser known, naturalist, naturalism, history, historical, biography, biographical, personal life, career, selection, natural, modern, thinker.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226731780423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226731780/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles